Anonymous Fri 18 Aug 2023 16:13:12 No.58888748 Report
Quoted By: >>58888791 >>58889257
>>58886926
The MON90? That's pretty crazy. Thing about it is, though, that it weights almost eight times what a Claymore does, but has less than double the effective lethal range. Part of it is the square-cube law. Part of it is that the Russians are using cylindrical preformed fragments that scatter more than the spherical steel pellets in the Claymore. The Claymore throws its pellets in a narrow fan shape, sixty degrees wide by only one and a half degrees tall. I can't find any information on whether the Russian almost-copies are as good at reducing vertical dispersion, but my gut says no.

>>58887027
It's in the designation. MON90 = lethal range 90m. Danger space is "up to" 325m in front. Because If it's not placed immediately in front of an earthen berm or something similar, it has a danger space of up to 125m to the rear, and similar danger space to the sides. The MON90 is a big bitch. A Claymore weighs less than four pounds. The MON90 weighs almost 27 pounds and is over half explosive filler by weight, though sources are contradictory over whether the Russians used a plastic bonded explosive or pure RDX (that's a spicy-a meatball!) as the fill.

The MON50 seems to be closer to a straight-up Claymore copy, but it's still heavier than Claymore. The Russians have other directional antipersonnel mines, up to an MON200 that is a yuge circular concave thing that has to be set up on a tripod.

>>58887281
The amusing thing about the FFV013 is that the Swedes, after bitching in the UN for decades about the cruelty and perfidy of land mines, are still building the things, and saying "oh no, it's an antitank weapon. Perfectly legal, my dudes." Swedish NGOs have spent thirty years screaming about how evil the US is for having landmines. Försvarets Fabriksverk is still manufacturing the FFV013 and others. They are currently exporting them.

But this is depressing. Here, have not one bnuuy, but two. Aren't they cute? Aren't they pretty?

Anonymous Fri 18 Aug 2023 16:52:17 No.58889503 Report
Quoted By:
>>58889257
The Claymore uses inexpensive spherical soft mild steel pellets because on detonation and acceleration, air resistance stretches them into long skinny shapes that are more aerodynamic. They are not stable, of course, but for the mine's purpose, they're good enough, out to 90-100m, anyway. Early experimental versions of the Claymore used hardened steel pellets, which tended to shatter into small particles when the shock wave from the explosive fill hit them. Production versions of the Claymore since 1960 or thereabouts have had a "pusher plate" made of plastic and aluminum foil separating the fragments from the explosive charge. It's cheap, it only weighs a few ounces, and it boosts velocities and helps keep the pellets intact. I don't have information about the cylindrical preformed fragments the Russians like so much, but I will guess they're not anything expensive.
